### Functional Explanation
This module performs a multiply-accumulate (MAC) operation: it multiplies two 16-bit inputs `a` and `b`, adds a 16-bit input `c`, and registers the 32-bit result.

### Potential Issues
1. **Poor DSP Utilization / Timing**: In modern FPGAs (like Xilinx DSP48E1/E2 blocks), the DSP slices have dedicated input registers, multiplier stages, adder stages, and output registers. The current code has inputs driving the multiplier and adder combinationally before the final register. This limits the maximum clock frequency (Fmax) because the entire multiplication and addition happens in a single clock cycle.

### Fix
To optimally utilize DSP slice pipelining and achieve maximum Fmax (e.g., >400MHz), add input and intermediate pipeline registers. The synthesis tool will absorb them into the DSP block.
```verilog
module mult_add_opt(input clk, input [15:0] a, b, c, output reg [31:0] res);
  // Input registers
  reg [15:0] a_reg, b_reg, c_reg;
  // Multiplier register
  reg [31:0] mult_reg;

  always @(posedge clk) begin
    // Stage 1: Register inputs (maps to DSP INMODE/A/B/C registers)
    a_reg <= a;
    b_reg <= b;
    c_reg <= c;

    // Stage 2: Register multiplier output (maps to DSP M register)
    mult_reg <= a_reg * b_reg;

    // Stage 3: Register final addition (maps to DSP P register)
    res <= mult_reg + c_reg;
  end
endmodule
```
